;; **
;;; Brute forcing always returns the optimal solution.  
;;; However, the complexity of this algorithm is `O(n!)`, which means that even if a machine can check 2 million tours per seconds, it would still take around 120 days to examine all of the tours for 16 cities (16! = 20922789888000 tours).
;; **

;; **
;;; ## Nearest Neighbour Algorithm
;;; 
;;; Unlike the brute force algorithm, nearest neighbour algorithm is an **approximation algorithm** in which it will not always give you the best solution, but something close to it.
;;; 
;;; This is also a type of **greedy search** as it always select the nearest city as the next destination.
;;; 
;;; 1. Start at some city, by default we start at the first city in the set of cities passed in
;;; 1. extend the tour by ...
;;; 1. ... finding the next nearest city
;;; 1. ... that has not been visited
;; **

;; @@
(defn nearest-neighbour [current unvisited-cities]
  (apply min-key (partial distance current) unvisited-cities))
